# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: duncan-mcfarlan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/9th-united-states-congress] The **9th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/9th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C., from March 4, 1805, to March 4, 1807, during the fifth and sixth years of Thomas Jefferson's presidency.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/9th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1800 United States census.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/9th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had a Democratic-Republican majority.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/9th-united-states-congress] The count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this Congress.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/9th-united-states-congress] Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the "Changes in membership" section.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/9th-united-states-congress] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/9th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed by class, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/9th-united-states-congress] Senators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/9th-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/9th-united-states-congress] The count below reflects changes from the beginning of this Congress.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/9th-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] The ***Biographical Directory of the United States Congress*** (**Bioguide**) is a biographical dictionary of all present and former members of the United States Congress and its predecessors, the Continental Congress and the Confederation Congress.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] Also included are Delegates from territories and the District of Columbia and Resident Commissioners from the Philippines and Puerto Rico.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] The online edition has a guide to the research collections of institutions where a member's papers, letters, correspondence, and other items are archived, as well as an extended bibliography of published works concerning the member (a shorter bibliography is included with the member's biography).
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] These additional resources, when available, can be accessed via links at the left side of the member's page on the website.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] Charles Lanman, author, journalist, and former secretary to Daniel Webster, gathered the first collection of biographies of former and sitting members of Congress for his *Dictionary of Congress*, published by J.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] Lanman intended his *Dictionary of the United States Congress* to serve as a guide for sitting Members of Congress, similar to the modern *Congressional Directory*.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] In 1864, the House of Representatives and the Senate approved the publication of an updated version of Lanman's *Dictionary of Congress* by the new Government Printing Office.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] In the late 1860s Congress offered Benjamin Perley Poore, a journalist and clerk of the Senate Committee on Printing and Records, the job of preparing a *Congressional Directory* with biographical sketches and the kind of reference information found in the *Dictionary of Congress*.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] In anticipation of the centenary of American independence and in search of a market not served by Poore's *Congressional Directory*, Lanman prepared the *Biographical Annals of the Civil Government of the United States*, published by James Anglim of Washington, D.C. in 1876.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] This volume combined the biographies of the *Dictionary of Congress* with entries for other governmental officials since 1776 and expanded reference tables.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] Poore offered a competing historical volume in 1878 with his *Political Register and Congressional Directory*, published by Houghton, Osgood and Company, Boston.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] Morrison's revision of Lanman's *Biographical Annals* (New York, 1887) was the final directory of congressional biography to be prepared and published privately.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] In 1903 Congress authorized the publication of *A Biographical Congressional Directory, 1774 to 1903*.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] Enyart, this was the first volume prepared by congressional staff who drew on the Lanman and Poore editions as well as biographical information printed in the *Congressional Directory* since the 40th United States Congress (1867).
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] The most thorough and systematic revision of biographical entries attempted prior to the Bicentennial Edition (1989) was conducted in preparation for the *Biographical Directory of the American Congress, 1774–1927*.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] Ansel Wold, chief clerk of the Joint Committee on Printing, directed the compilation of this volume published in 1928.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] The 1920s survey yielded more detailed and consistent biographies than those in the nineteenth-century editions or in the earlier volumes compiled by congressional staff, but its frequent reliance on family legends and personal recollections introduced dubious information.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] Although Congress authorized updates that were published in 1949–50, 1961, and 1971, the entries from the 1928 edition remained virtually intact in the three subsequent editions.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] The creation of the Senate Historical Office in 1975 and the Office for the Bicentennial in the United States House of Representatives in 1983 provided the first opportunity for professional historians to revise and update the Biographical Directory.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] Earlier editions of the Biographical Directory and their nineteenth century predecessors offered little information on congressional careers other than terms of service.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] The bicentennial edition (1989) provided a more complete record of the individual members' years in office.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] A 1996 edition was published by *Congressional Quarterly*, but did not achieve wide circulation because of its much higher price.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] Congress issued an updated print edition in 2005.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] The development and growing use of the Internet in the 1990s led to the creation of websites for the House of Representatives and the Senate.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] Ray Strong, House Historian and Assistant to the Clerk of the House, advocated publication of the entries from the Biographical Directory on the Internet.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] Through the efforts of Joe Carmel, Cindy S.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] Internet technology offered the capability to update the Biographical Directory on a daily basis.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] Besides the biographies, the online database includes extensive bibliographies and a guide to all available research collections for Senate and House entries.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] The project was the first SGML/XML project for the House and Senate and paved the way for the drafting of legislation in XML in both chambers.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] The publicly available online directory has benefited from updated information provided to the House Office of the Historian and the Senate Historical Office from scholars, librarians, genealogists, and family members.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] Senate entries are accompanied by an image of the Senator, when available.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] Online House entries include images for Members and Speakers with official oil portraits and members since the 109th United States Congress (2005).
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/biographical-directory-of-the-united-states-congress] The records are maintained by staff in the House Office of the Historian and the Senate Office of the Historian.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The **Constitution of the United States** is the supreme law of the United States of America.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] It superseded the Articles of Confederation, the nation's first constitution, on March 4, 1789.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Originally including seven articles, the Constitution defined the foundational structure of the federal government.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The drafting of the Constitution by many of the nation's Founding Fathers, often referred to as its framing, was completed at the Constitutional Convention, which assembled at Independence Hall in Philadelphia between May 25 and September 17, 1787.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Articles IV, V, and VI embody concepts of federalism, describing the rights and responsibilities of state governments, the states in relationship to the federal government, and the process of constitutional amendment.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Article VII establishes the procedure used to ratify the constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Since the Constitution became operational in 1789, it has been amended 27 times.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The first ten amendments, known collectively as the Bill of Rights, offer specific protections of individual liberty and justice and place restrictions on the powers of government within the U.S. states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Amendments 13–15 are known as the Reconstruction Amendments.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The majority of the later amendments expand individual civil rights protections, with some addressing issues related to federal authority or modifying government processes and procedures.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Amendments to the United States Constitution, unlike ones made to many constitutions worldwide, are appended to the document.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Constitution of the United States is the oldest and longest-standing written and codified national constitution in force in the world.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The first permanent constitution, it has been interpreted, supplemented, and implemented by a large body of federal constitutional law and has influenced the constitutions of other nations.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] From September 5, 1774, to March 1, 1781, the Second Continental Congress, convened in Philadelphia in what is now Independence Hall, functioned as the provisional government of the United States.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Delegates to the First Continental Congress in 1774 and then the Second Continental Congress from 1775 to 1781 were chosen largely from the revolutionary committees of correspondence in various colonies rather than through the colonial governments of the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union was the first constitution of the United States.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The document was drafted by a committee appointed by the Second Continental Congress in mid-June 1777 and was adopted by the full Congress in mid-November of that year.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Ratification by the 13 colonies took more than three years and was completed March 1, 1781.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Articles gave little power to the central government.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] While the Confederation Congress had some decision-making abilities, it lacked enforcement powers.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The implementation of most decisions, including amendments to the Articles, required legislative approval by all 13 of the newly formed states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Despite these limitations, based on the Congressional authority granted in Article 9, the league of states was considered as strong as any similar republican confederation ever formed.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The chief problem was, in the words of George Washington, "no money".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Confederated Congress could print money, but it was worthless, and while the Congress could borrow money, it could not pay it back.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] No state paid its share of taxes to support the government, and some paid nothing.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] A few states met the interest payments toward the national debt owed by their citizens, but nothing greater, and no interest was paid on debts owed to foreign governments.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] By 1786, the United States was facing default on its outstanding debts.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Under the Articles, the United States had little ability to defend its sovereignty.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Most of the troops in the nation's 625-man army were deployed facing non-threatening British forts on American soil.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Soldiers were not being paid, some were deserting, and others were threatening mutiny.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Spain closed New Orleans to American commerce, despite the protests of U.S. officials.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] When Barbary pirates began seizing American ships of commerce, the Treasury had no funds to pay toward ransom.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] If a military crisis required action, the Congress had no credit or taxing power to finance a response.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Domestically, the Articles of Confederation was failing to bring unity to the diverse sentiments and interests of the various states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Although the Treaty of Paris in 1783 was signed between Britain and the U.S., and named each of the American states, various states proceeded to violate it.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] New York and South Carolina repeatedly prosecuted Loyalists for wartime activity and redistributed their lands.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Individual state legislatures independently laid embargoes, negotiated directly with foreign authorities, raised armies, and made war, all violating the letter and the spirit of the Articles.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] In September 1786, during the inter–state Annapolis convention to discuss and develop a consensus about reversing the protectionist trade barriers that each state had erected, James Madison questioned whether the Articles of Confederation was a binding compact or even a viable government.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Connecticut paid nothing and "positively refused" to pay U.S. assessments for two years.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] A rumor at the time was that a seditious party of New York legislators had opened a conversation with the Viceroy of Canada.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] To the south, the British were said to be openly funding Creek Indian raids on Georgia, and the state was under martial law.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Additionally, during Shays' Rebellion (August 1786 – June 1787) in Massachusetts, Congress could provide no money to support an endangered constituent state.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] General Benjamin Lincoln was obliged to raise funds from Boston merchants to pay for a volunteer army.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Congress could do nothing significant without nine states, and some legislation required all 13.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] When a state produced only one member in attendance, its vote was not counted.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] If a state's delegation was evenly divided, its vote could not be counted towards the nine-count requirement.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Congress of the Confederation had "virtually ceased trying to govern".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The vision of a respectable nation among nations seemed to be fading in the eyes of revolutionaries such as George Washington, Benjamin Franklin, and Rufus King.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Their dream of a republic, a nation without hereditary rulers, with power derived from the people in frequent elections, was in doubt.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] On February 21, 1787, the Confederation Congress called a convention of state delegates in Philadelphia to propose revisions to the Articles.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Unlike earlier attempts, the convention was not meant for new laws or piecemeal alterations, but for the "sole and express purpose of revising the Articles of Confederation".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The convention was not limited to commerce but intended to "render the federal constitution adequate to the exigencies of government and the preservation of the Union".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] On the appointed day, May 14, 1787, only the Virginia and Pennsylvania delegations were present, and the convention's opening meeting was postponed for lack of a quorum.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] A quorum of seven states met on May 25, and deliberations began.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Eventually 12 states were represented, with Rhode Island refusing to participate.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Of the 74 delegates appointed by the states, 55 attended.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The convention's initial mandate was limited to amending the Articles of Confederation, which had proven highly ineffective in meeting the young nation's needs.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Almost immediately, however, the delegates began considering measures to replace the Articles of Confederation.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] On May 31, the Convention devolved into the Committee of the Whole, charged with considering the Virginia Plan.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] On June 13, the Virginia resolutions in amended form were reported out of committee.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The New Jersey Plan was put forward in response to the Virginia Plan.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] On June 19, 1787, delegates rejected the New Jersey Plan with three states voting in favor, seven against, and one divided.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The plan's defeat led to a series of compromises centering primarily on two issues: slavery and proportional representation.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Proposals by Madison (Virginia) and Wilson (Pennsylvania) called for a supreme court veto over national legislation.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] This proposal resembled the system in New York, where the Constitution of 1777 called for a "Council of Revision" by the governor and justices of the state supreme court, which council would review and veto any passed legislation.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Madison's proposal was defeated three times and replaced by a presidential veto with congressional override.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The justification for judicial review is to be explicitly found in the open ratifications held in the states and reported in their newspapers.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] John Marshall in Virginia, James Wilson in Pennsylvania and Oliver Ellsworth of Connecticut all argued for Supreme Court judicial review of acts of state legislature.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] 78, Alexander Hamilton advocated the doctrine of a written document held as a superior enactment of the people.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] "A limited constitution can be preserved in practice no other way" than through courts which can declare void any legislation contrary to the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The issue of proportional representation was of concern to less populous states, which under the Articles had the same power as larger states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] From July 2 to 16, a Committee of Eleven, including one delegate from each state represented, met to work out a compromise on the issue of representation in the federal legislature.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] All agreed to a republican form of government grounded in representing the people in the states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] For the legislature, two issues were to be decided: (i) how the votes were to be allocated among the states in the Congress, and (ii) how the representatives should be elected.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Great Compromise ended the stalemate between patriots and nationalists, leading to numerous other compromises in a spirit of accommodation.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The issue of slavery pitted Northern states, where slavery was slowly being abolished, against Southern states, whose agricultural economies depended on slave labor.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] To satisfy interests in the South, the delegates agreed to protect the slave trade for 20 years.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Further compromises were also made on presidential term, powers, and method of selection, as well as the jurisdiction of the federal judiciary.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] While these compromises held the Union together and aided the Constitution's ratification, slavery continued for eight more decades, and less populous states continue to have disproportional representation in the U.S.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Convention recessed from July 26 to August 6 to await the report of this "Committee of Detail".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Overall, the report of the committee conformed to the resolutions adopted by the convention, adding some elements.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] A twenty-three article (plus preamble) constitution was presented.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] From August 6 to September 10, the report of the committee of detail was discussed, section by section and clause by clause.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Details were attended to, and further compromises were effected.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The final draft, presented to the convention on September 12, contained seven articles, a preamble and a closing endorsement, of which Morris was the primary author.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The committee also presented a proposed letter to accompany the constitution when delivered to Congress.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Constitution was handwritten on five pages of parchment by Jacob Shallus.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The final document was taken up on Monday, September 17, at the convention's final session.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Several of the delegates were disappointed in the result, a makeshift series of unfortunate compromises.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Some delegates left before the ceremony and three others refused to sign.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The advocates of the Constitution were anxious to obtain unanimous support of all twelve states represented in the convention.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Their accepted formula for the closing endorsement was "Done in Convention, by the unanimous consent of the States present".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] At the end of the convention, the proposal was agreed to by eleven state delegations and the lone remaining delegate from New York, Alexander Hamilton.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Within three days of its signing on September 17, 1787, the Constitution was submitted to the Congress of the Confederation, then sitting in New York City, the nation's temporary capital.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The document, originally intended as a revision of the Articles of Confederation, instead introduced a completely new form of government.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] While members of Congress had the power to reject it, they voted unanimously on September 28 to forward the proposal to the thirteen states for their ratification.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Under the process outlined in Article VII of the proposed Constitution, the state legislatures were tasked with organizing "Federal Conventions" to ratify the document.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] This process ignored the amendment provision of the Articles of Confederation which required unanimous approval of all the states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Instead, Article VII called for ratification by just nine of the 13 states—a two-thirds majority.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Two factions soon emerged, one supporting the Constitution, the Federalists, and the other opposing it, the so-called Anti-Federalists.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Over the ensuing months, the proposal was debated, criticized, and expounded upon clause by clause.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] In the state of New York, at the time a hotbed of anti-Federalism, three delegates from the Philadelphia Convention who were also members of the Congress—Hamilton, Madison, and Jay—published a series of commentaries, now known as *The Federalist Papers*, in support of ratification.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Before year's end, three state legislatures voted in favor of ratification.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Delaware was first, voting unanimously 30–0; Pennsylvania second, approving the measure 46–23; and New Jersey third, also recording a unanimous vote.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] As 1788 began, Connecticut and Georgia followed Delaware's lead with almost unanimous votes, but the outcome became less certain as leaders in key states such as Virginia, New York, and Massachusetts expressed concerns over the lack of protections for people's rights.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Fearing the prospect of defeat, the Federalists relented, promising that if the Constitution was adopted, amendments would be added to secure individual liberties.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] With that, the anti-Federalists' position collapsed.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] On June 21, 1788, New Hampshire became the ninth state to ratify.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] As its final act, the Congress of Confederation agreed to acquire 100 square miles of land from Maryland and Virginia for establishing a permanent capital.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] North Carolina waited to ratify the Constitution until after the Bill of Rights was passed by the new Congress, and Rhode Island's ratification would only come after a threatened trade embargo.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court was initially made up of jurists who had been intimately connected with the framing of the Constitution and the establishment of its government as law.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] John Jay (New York), a co-author of *The Federalist Papers*, served as chief justice for the first six years.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The second chief justice, John Rutledge (South Carolina), was appointed by Washington in 1795 as a recess appointment, but was not confirmed by the Senate.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Resigning later that year, he was succeeded in 1796 by the third chief justice, Oliver Ellsworth (Connecticut).
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Both Rutledge and Ellsworth were delegates to the Constitutional Convention.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] John Marshall (Virginia), the fourth chief justice, had served in the Virginia Ratification Convention in 1788.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] His 34 years of service on the Court would see some of the most important rulings to help establish the nation the Constitution had begun.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Other early members of the Supreme Court who had been delegates to the Constitutional Convention included James Wilson (Pennsylvania) for ten years, and John Blair Jr.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Section 1, Article 3 provides that Congress can create lower (or "inferior") courts.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Judiciary Act of 1789 saw Congress's first exercise of such power.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Code describes judicial powers and administration.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] As of the First Congress, the Supreme Court justices rode circuit to sit as panels to hear appeals from the district courts.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] In 1891, Congress enacted a new system, where district courts would have original jurisdiction; intermediate appellate circuit courts with exclusive jurisdiction heard regional appeals before consideration by the Supreme Court; and the Supreme Court holds discretionary jurisdiction.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] No part of the Constitution expressly authorizes judicial review, but the framers did contemplate the idea, and precedent has since established that the courts could exercise judicial review over the actions of Congress or the executive branch.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] To establish a federal system of national law, considerable effort goes into developing a spirit of comity between federal government and states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] By the doctrine of res judicata, federal courts give "full faith and credit" to State Courts.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court will decide Constitutional issues of state law only on a case-by-case basis, and only by strict Constitutional necessity, independent of state legislators' motives, their policy outcomes or its national wisdom.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Two conflicting federal laws are under "pendent" jurisdiction if one presents a strict constitutional issue.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Federal court jurisdiction is rare when a state legislature enacts something as under federal jurisdiction.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Clauses 4 and 9 of Article One, Section 9 were explicitly shielded from Constitutional amendment prior to 1808.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] On January 1, 1808, the first day it was permitted to do so, Congress approved legislation prohibiting the importation of slaves into the country.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] On February 3, 1913, with ratification of the Sixteenth Amendment, Congress gained the authority to levy an income tax without apportioning it among the states or basing it on the United States Census.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Constitution was a federal one and was greatly influenced by the study of Magna Carta and other federations, both ancient and extant.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Due Process Clause of the Constitution was partly based on common law and on Magna Carta (1215), which had become a foundation of English liberty against arbitrary power wielded by a ruler.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The idea of Separation of Powers inherent in the Constitution was largely inspired by eighteenth-century Enlightenment philosophers, such as Montesquieu and John Locke.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The influence of Montesquieu, Locke, Edward Coke and William Blackstone were evident at the Constitutional Convention.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Prior to and during the framing and signing of the Constitution, Blackstone, Hume, Locke and Montesquieu were among the political philosophers most frequently referred to.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] James Madison, for example made frequent reference to Blackstone, Locke, and Montesquieu, who were among the most prominent political theorists of the late eighteenth century.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] In a speech at the Constitutional Convention Franklin stated, "We have gone back to ancient history for models of Government, and examined different forms of those Republics ...
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] And we have viewed modern States all round Europe but find none of their Constitutions suitable to our circumstances." Jefferson maintained, that most European governments were autocratic monarchies and not compatible with the egalitarian character of the American people.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Greene maintains that by 1776 the founders drew heavily upon Magna Carta and the later writings of "Enlightenment rationalism" and English common law.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] In his *Institutes of the Lawes of England*, Coke interpreted Magna Carta protections and rights to apply not just to nobles, but to all British subjects.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] In writing the Virginia Charter of 1606, he enabled the King in Parliament to give those to be born in the colonies all rights and liberties as though they were born in England.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] William Blackstone's *Commentaries on the Laws of England* are considered the most influential books on law in the new republic.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The English Bill of Rights (1689) was an inspiration for the American Bill of Rights.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Both require jury trials, contain a right to keep and bear arms, prohibit excessive bail and forbid "cruel and unusual punishments".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Many liberties protected by state constitutions and the Virginia Declaration of Rights were incorporated into the Bill of Rights.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Upon the arrival of the American Revolution, many of the rights guaranteed by the Federal Bill of Rights were recognized as being inspired by English law.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] A substantial body of thought had been developed from the literature of republicanism in the United States, typically demonstrated by the works of John Adams, who often quoted Blackstone and Montesquieu verbatim, and applied to the creation of state constitutions.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Schneider held that the Scottish Enlightenment was "probably the most potent single tradition in the American Enlightenment" and the advancement of personal liberties.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Historian Daniel Walker Howe notes that Benjamin Franklin greatly admired David Hume, an eighteenth-century Scottish philosopher, and had studied many of his works while at Edinburgh in 1760.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Both embraced the idea that high-ranking public officials should receive no salary and that the lower class was a better judge of character when it came to choosing their representatives.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Following the Glorious Revolution of 1688, British political philosopher John Locke was a major influence, expanding on the contract theory of government advanced by Thomas Hobbes, his contemporary.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Locke advanced the principle of consent of the governed in his *Two Treatises of Government*.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Government's duty under a social contract among the sovereign people was to serve the people by protecting their rights.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] These basic rights were life, liberty, and property.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Montesquieu's influence on the framers is evident in Madison's *Federalist No.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Thomas Jefferson, Adams, and Mason were known to read Montesquieu.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Montesquieu emphasized the need for balanced forces pushing against each other to prevent tyranny (reflecting the influence of Polybius's 2nd century BC treatise on the checks and balances of the Roman Republic).
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Supreme Court Justices, the ultimate interpreters of the constitution, have also cited Montesquieu throughout the Court's history.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Administrator of General Services**, 433 U.S.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] American Indian history scholars Donald Grinde and Bruce Johansen claim there is "overwhelming evidence" that Iroquois Confederacy political concepts and ideas influenced the U.S.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Constitution, and are considered to be the most outspoken supporters of the Iroquois thesis.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The most outspoken critic, anthropologist Elisabeth Tooker, claimed the Iroquois influence thesis is largely the product of "white interpretations of Indians" and "scholarly misapprehension".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] John Napoleon Brinton Hewitt, who was born on the Tuscarora Indian Reservation, and was an ethnologist at the Smithsonian Institution's Bureau of Ethnology is often cited by historians of Iroquois history.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Hewitt, however, rejected the idea that the Iroquois League had a major influence on the Albany Plan of Union, Benjamin Franklin's plan to create a unified government for the Thirteen Colonies, which was rejected.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Constitution includes four sections: an introductory paragraph titled Preamble, a list of seven Articles that define the government's framework, an untitled closing endorsement with the signatures of 39 framers.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] 27 amendments have also been adopted under Article V.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The opening words, "We the People", represented a new thought: the idea that the people and not the states were the source of the government's legitimacy.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Coined by Gouverneur Morris of Pennsylvania, who chaired the convention's Committee of Style, the phrase is considered an improvement on the section's original draft which followed the words *We the People* with a list of the 13 states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] In place of the names of the states Morris substituted "of the United States" and then listed the Constitution's six goals, none of which were mentioned originally.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The signing of the United States Constitution occurred on September 17, 1787, when 39 delegates endorsed the constitution created during the convention.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] In addition to signatures, this closing endorsement, the Constitution's eschatocol, included a brief declaration that the delegates' work has been successfully completed and that those whose signatures appear on it subscribe to the final document.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Included are a statement pronouncing the document's adoption by the states present, a formulaic dating of its adoption, and the delegates' signatures.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Additionally, the convention's secretary, William Jackson, added a note to verify four amendments made by hand to the final document, and signed the note to authenticate its validity.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The language of the concluding endorsement, conceived by Gouverneur Morris and presented to the convention by Benjamin Franklin, was made intentionally ambiguous in hopes of winning over the votes of dissenting delegates.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Advocates for the new frame of government, realizing the impending difficulty of obtaining the consent of the states needed to make it operational, were anxious to obtain the unanimous support of the delegations from each state.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] It was feared that many of the delegates would refuse to give their individual assent to the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Therefore, in order that the action of the convention would appear to be unanimous, the formula, *Done in convention by the unanimous consent of the states present ...* was devised.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Constitution's main provisions include seven articles that define the basic framework of the federal government.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Articles that have been amended still include the original text, although provisions repealed by amendments under Article V are usually bracketed or italicized to indicate they no longer apply.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Article I describes the Congress, the legislative branch of the federal government: Congress comprises both the Senate and House of Representatives; members of both houses are subject to age, citizenship, and state residency requirements; and are elected by the people of a state.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Section 3, Clause 1 provides for equal representation of the states in the Senate.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Section 8 enumerates the powers delegated to the legislature and includes broad provisions such as the General Welfare Clause (also known as the Taxing and Spending Clause), Commerce Clause, and Necessary and Proper Clause.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Section 9 lists eight specific limits on congressional power.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Section 9, Clause 1 prevents Congress from passing any law that would restrict the importation of slaves into the United States prior to 1808.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Clause 4 holds that direct taxes must be apportioned according to state populations.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Article II describes the office, qualifications, and duties of the president of the United States and the vice president.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Article is modified by the 12th Amendment, which regulates presidential elections, and the 25th Amendment, relating to office succession.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The president is head of the executive branch of the federal government; the nation's head of state and head of government; and the Commander in Chief of the United States Armed Forces, as well as of state militias when they are mobilized.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The president makes treaties with the advice and consent of the Senate.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] To administer the federal government, the president commissions all the offices of the federal government as Congress directs; and may require the opinions of its principal officers and make "recess appointments" for vacancies that may happen during the recess of the Senate.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The president ensures the laws are faithfully executed and may grant reprieves and pardons with the exception of Congressional impeachment.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The president reports to Congress on the State of the Union, and by the Recommendation Clause, recommends "necessary and expedient" national measures.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The president may convene and adjourn Congress under special circumstances.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Section 4 provides for the removal of the president and other federal officers.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The president is removed on impeachment for, and conviction of, treason, bribery, or other high crimes and misdemeanors.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Article III describes the court system, including the Supreme Court.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Section 1 vests the judicial power of the United States in federal courts and, with it, the authority to interpret and apply the law to particular cases.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Also included is the power to punish, sentence, and direct future action to resolve conflicts.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Implied powers under Article III include the enforcement of judicial decisions through criminal contempt and civil contempt powers; injunctive relief and the habeas corpus remedy; and the ability to imprison for contumacy, bad-faith litigation, and failure to obey a writ of mandamus.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Clause 1 of Section 2, known as the Case or Controversy Clause, authorizes the federal courts to hear actual cases and controversies only.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Their judicial power does not extend to cases that are hypothetical, or which are proscribed due to standing, mootness, or ripeness issues.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Generally, a case or controversy requires the presence of adverse parties who have some interest genuinely at stake in the case.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Section 2 also protects the right to trial by jury in all criminal cases.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Section 3 bars Congress from changing or modifying Federal law on treason by simple majority.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] This section also defines treason as an overt act of making war or materially helping those at war with the United States.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Article IV outlines the relations among the states and between each state and the federal government.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] It also provides for such matters as admitting new states, border changes between the states, and extradition between the states, as well as laying down a legal basis for freedom of movement and travel among the states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Full Faith and Credit Clause requires states to recognise the public acts, records, and court proceedings of the other states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Congress is permitted to regulate the manner in which proof of such acts may be admitted.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The "privileges and immunities" clause prohibits state governments from discriminating against citizens of other states in favor of resident citizens.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] For instance, in criminal sentencing, a state may not increase a penalty on the grounds that the convicted person is a non-resident.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Territorial Clause gives Congress the power to make rules for disposing of federal property and governing non-state territories of the United States.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Finally, the fourth section of Article Four requires the United States to guarantee to each state a republican form of government and to protect them from invasion and violence.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Article V outlines the process for amending the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The Articles of Confederation provided that amendments were to be proposed by Congress and ratified by the unanimous vote of all 13 state legislatures.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] This proved to be a major flaw in the Articles, as it created an insurmountable obstacle to constitutional reform.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The amendment process crafted during the Philadelphia Constitutional Convention was, according to The Federalist No.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] 43, designed to establish a balance between pliancy and rigidity.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Article Five ends by shielding certain clauses in the Constitution from being amended.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Article VI establishes that the Constitution and all federal laws and treaties made in accordance with it have supremacy over state laws, and that "the judges in every state shall be bound thereby, any thing in the laws or constitutions of any state notwithstanding".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] It validates national debt created under the Articles of Confederation and requires that all federal and state legislators, officers, and judges take oaths or affirmations to support the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] This means that the states' constitutions and laws should not conflict with the laws of the federal constitution and that in case of a conflict, state judges are legally bound to honor the federal laws and constitution over those of any state.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Article Six also states "no religious Test shall ever be required as a Qualification to any Office or public Trust under the United States".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Article VII describes the process for establishing the proposed new frame of government.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Anticipating that the influence of many state politicians would be Antifederalist, delegates to the Philadelphia Convention provided for ratification of the Constitution by popularly elected ratifying conventions in each state.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] The convention method also made it possible that judges, ministers and others ineligible to serve in state legislatures, could be elected to a convention.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Suspecting that Rhode Island, at least, might not ratify, delegates decided that the Constitution would go into effect as soon as nine states (two-thirds rounded up) ratified.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p01] Each of the remaining four states could then join the newly formed union by ratifying.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The procedure for amending the Constitution is outlined in Article V and is currently overseen by the archivist of the United States.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Between 1949 and 1985, it was overseen by the administrator of General Services, and before that by the secretary of state.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Under Article V, a proposal for an amendment must be adopted either by two-thirds of both houses of Congress or by a national convention that had been requested by two-thirds of the state legislatures.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Following this, Congress decides whether the proposed amendment is to be ratified by state legislatures or state ratifying conventions.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The proposed amendment along with the method of ratification is sent to the Office of the Federal Register, which copies it in slip law format and submits it to the states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] To date, the convention method of proposal has never been tried and the convention method of ratification has only been used once, for the Twenty-first Amendment.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] A proposed amendment becomes an operative part of the Constitution as soon as it is ratified by three-fourths of the States (currently 38 of the 50 states).
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] No additional action by Congress or anyone else after ratification is required.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] When the Office of the Federal Register verifies that it has received the required number of authenticated ratification documents, it drafts a formal proclamation for the Archivist to certify that the amendment is valid.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] This certification is published in the *Federal Register* and *United States Statutes at Large* and serves as official notice to Congress and the nation that the ratification process has been completed.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Constitution has twenty-seven amendments.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Structurally, the Constitution's original text and all prior amendments remain untouched.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The precedent for this practice was set in 1789, when Congress considered and proposed the first several Constitutional amendments.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Among these, Amendments 1–10 are collectively known as the Bill of Rights, and Amendments 13–15 are known as the Reconstruction Amendments.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Excluding the Twenty-seventh Amendment, which was pending before the states for 202 years, 225 days, the longest pending amendment that was successfully ratified was the Twenty-second Amendment, which took 3 years, 343 days.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Twenty-sixth Amendment was ratified in the shortest time, 100 days.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The average ratification time for the first twenty-six amendments was 1 year, 252 days; for all twenty-seven, 9 years, 48 days.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The first ten Amendments introduced were referred to as the Bill of Rights which consists of 10 amendments that were added to the Constitution in 1791, as supporters of the Constitution had promised critics during the debates of 1788.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The First Amendment prohibits Congress from obstructing the exercise of certain individual freedoms: freedom of religion, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, freedom of assembly, and right to petition.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Its Free Exercise Clause guarantees a person's right to hold whatever religious beliefs they want, and to freely exercise that belief; its Establishment Clause prevents the federal government from creating an official national church or favoring one set of religious beliefs over another.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Second Amendment protects the right of individuals to keep and bear arms.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Supreme Court has ruled that this right applies to individuals, not merely to collective militias.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It has also held that the government may regulate or place some limits on the manufacture, ownership and sale of firearms or other weapons.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Requested by several states during the constitutional ratification debates, the amendment followed the efforts of the British to confiscate the colonists' firearms at the outbreak of the Revolutionary War.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Third Amendment prohibits the federal government from forcing individuals to provide lodging to soldiers in their homes during peacetime without their consent.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Requested by several states during the Constitutional ratification debates, the amendment reflected the lingering resentment over the Quartering Acts passed by the British Parliament during the Revolutionary War, which had allowed British soldiers to take over private homes for their own use.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Fourth Amendment protects people against unreasonable searches and seizures of either self or property by government officials.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] A search can mean everything from a frisking by a police officer or to a demand for a blood test to a search of an individual's home or car.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] A seizure occurs when the government takes control of an individual or something in the possession of the individual.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Items that are seized often are used as evidence when the individual is charged with a crime.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It also imposes certain limitations on police investigating a crime and prevents the use of illegally obtained evidence at trial.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Additionally, the Fifth Amendment also prohibits government from taking private property for public use without "just compensation", the basis of eminent domain in the United States.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Sixth Amendment provides several protections and rights to an individual accused of a crime.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The accused has the right to a fair, speedy, and public trial by a local and impartial jury.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1966, the Supreme Court ruled that, with the Fifth Amendment, this amendment requires what has become known as the *Miranda* warning.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Seventh Amendment extends the right to a jury trial to federal civil cases, and inhibits courts from overturning a jury's findings of fact.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Although the Seventh Amendment itself says that it is limited to "suits at common law", meaning cases that triggered the right to a jury under English law, the amendment has been found to apply in lawsuits that are similar to the old common law cases.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] For example, the right to a jury trial applies to cases brought under federal statutes that prohibit race or gender discrimination in housing or employment.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] This amendment guarantees the right to a jury trial only in federal court, not in state court.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Eighth Amendment protects people from having bail or fines set at an amount so high that it would be impossible for all but the richest defendants to pay, and also protects people from being subjected to cruel and unusual punishment.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Although this phrase originally was intended to outlaw certain gruesome methods of punishment, it has been broadened over the years to protect against punishments that are grossly disproportionate to or too harsh for the particular crime.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] This provision has also been used to challenge prison conditions such as extremely unsanitary cells, overcrowding, insufficient medical care and deliberate failure by officials to protect inmates from one another.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Ninth Amendment declares that individuals have other fundamental rights, in addition to those stated in the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] During the Constitutional ratification debates, Anti-Federalists argued that a Bill of Rights should be added.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Federalists opposed it on grounds that a list would necessarily be incomplete but would be taken as explicit and exhaustive, thus enlarging the power of the federal government by implication.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Anti-Federalists persisted, and several state ratification conventions refused to ratify the Constitution without a more specific list of protections, so the First Congress added what became the Ninth Amendment as a compromise.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Because the rights protected by the Ninth Amendment are not specified, they are referred to as "unenumerated".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Supreme Court has found that unenumerated rights include such important rights as the right to travel, the right to vote, the right to privacy, and the right to make important decisions about one's health care or body.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Tenth Amendment (1791) was included in the Bill of Rights to further define the balance of power between the federal government and the states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The amendment states that the federal government has only those powers specifically granted by the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] These powers include the power to declare war, to collect taxes, to regulate interstate business activities and others that are listed in the articles or in subsequent constitutional amendments.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Any power not listed is, says the Tenth Amendment, left to the states or the people.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] While there is no specific list of what these "reserved powers" may be, the Supreme Court has ruled that laws affecting family relations, commerce within a state's own borders, abortion, and local law enforcement activities, are among those specifically reserved to the states or the people.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Eleventh Amendment specifically prohibits federal courts from hearing cases in which a state is sued by an individual from another state or another country, thus extending to the states sovereign immunity protection from certain types of legal liability.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Article Three, Section 2, Clause 1 has been affected by this amendment, which also overturned the Supreme Court's decision in *Chisholm v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Twelfth Amendment modifies the way the Electoral College chooses the president and vice president.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It stipulates that each elector must cast a distinct vote for president and vice president, instead of two votes for president.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It also suggests that the president and vice president should not be from the same state.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Article II, Section 1, Clause 3 is superseded by this amendment, which also extends the eligibility requirements to become president to the vice president.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Thirteenth Amendment (1865) abolished slavery and involuntary servitude, except as punishment for a crime, and authorized Congress to enforce abolition.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Though millions of slaves had been declared free by the 1863 Emancipation Proclamation, their post-Civil War status was unclear, as was the status of other millions.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Congress intended the Thirteenth Amendment to be a proclamation of freedom for all slaves throughout the nation and to take the question of emancipation away from politics.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] This amendment rendered inoperative or moot several of the original parts of the constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Fourteenth Amendment (1868) granted United States citizenship to former slaves and to all persons "subject to U.S. jurisdiction".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It also contained three new limits on state power: a state shall not violate a citizen's privileges or immunities; shall not deprive any person of life, liberty, or property without due process of law; and must guarantee all persons equal protection of the laws.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] These limitations dramatically expanded the protections of the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] This amendment, according to the Supreme Court's Doctrine of Incorporation, makes most provisions of the Bill of Rights applicable to state and local governments as well.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It superseded the mode of apportionment of representatives delineated in Article 1, Section 2, Clause 3, and also overturned the Supreme Court's decision in *Dred Scott v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Fifteenth Amendment (1870) prohibits the use of race, color, or previous condition of servitude in determining which citizens may vote.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The last of three post Civil War Reconstruction Amendments, it sought to abolish one of the key vestiges of slavery and to advance the civil rights and liberties of former slaves.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Sixteenth Amendment removed existing Constitutional constraints that limited the power of Congress to lay and collect taxes on income.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Specifically, the apportionment constraints delineated in Article 1, Section 9, Clause 4 have been removed by this amendment, which also overturned an 1895 Supreme Court decision, in *Pollock v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Farmers' Loan & Trust Co.*, that declared an unapportioned federal income tax on rents, dividends, and interest unconstitutional.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] This amendment has become the basis for all subsequent federal income tax legislation and has greatly expanded the scope of federal taxing and spending in the years since.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Seventeenth Amendment modifies the way senators are elected.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It stipulates that senators are to be elected by direct popular vote.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The amendment supersedes Article 1, Section 3, Clauses 1 and 2, under which the two senators from each state were elected by the state legislature.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It also allows state legislatures to permit their governors to make temporary appointments until a special election can be held.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Eighteenth Amendment (1919) prohibited the making, transporting, and selling of alcoholic beverages nationwide.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It also authorized Congress to enact legislation enforcing this prohibition.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Adopted at the urging of a national temperance movement, proponents believed that the use of alcohol was reckless and destructive and that prohibition would reduce crime and corruption, solve social problems, decrease the need for welfare and prisons, and improve the health of all Americans.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] During prohibition, it is estimated that alcohol consumption and alcohol related deaths declined dramatically.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] But prohibition had other, more negative consequences.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The amendment drove the lucrative alcohol business underground, giving rise to a large and pervasive black market.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] In addition, prohibition encouraged disrespect for the law and strengthened organized crime.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Prohibition came to an end in 1933, when this amendment was repealed.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Twenty-first Amendment (1933) repealed the Eighteenth Amendment and returned the regulation of alcohol to the states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Each state sets its own rules for the sale and importation of alcohol, including the drinking age.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Because a federal law provides federal funds to states that prohibit the sale of alcohol to minors under the age of twenty-one, all fifty states have set their drinking age there.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Rules about how alcohol is sold vary greatly from state to state.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Nineteenth Amendment prohibits the government from denying women the right to vote on the same terms as men.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Prior to the amendment's adoption, only a few states permitted women to vote and to hold office.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Twentieth Amendment changes the date on which a new president, vice president and Congress take office, thus shortening the time between Election Day and the beginning of presidential, vice presidential and congressional terms.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Originally, the Constitution provided that the annual meeting was to be on the first Monday in December unless otherwise provided by law.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] This meant that, when a new Congress was elected in November, it did not come into office until the following March, with a "lame duck" Congress convening in the interim.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] By moving the beginning of the president's new term from March 4 to January 20 (and in the case of Congress, to January 3), proponents hoped to put an end to lame duck sessions, while allowing for a speedier transition for the new administration and legislators.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Twenty-second Amendment limits an elected president to two terms in office, a total of eight years.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] However, under some circumstances it is possible for an individual to serve more than eight years.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Although nothing in the original frame of government limited how many presidential terms one could serve, the nation's first president, George Washington, declined to run for a third term, suggesting that two terms of four years were enough for any president.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] This precedent remained an unwritten rule of the presidency until broken by Franklin D.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt, who was elected to a third term as president 1940 and in 1944 to a fourth.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Twenty-third Amendment extends the right to vote in presidential elections to citizens residing in the District of Columbia by granting the District electors in the Electoral College, as if it were a state.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] When first established as the nation's capital in 1800, the District of Columbia's five thousand residents had neither a local government, nor the right to vote in federal elections.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] By 1960 the population of the District had grown to over 760,000.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Twenty-fourth Amendment prohibits a poll tax for voting.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Although passage of the Thirteenth, Fourteenth, and Fifteenth Amendments helped remove many of the discriminatory laws left over from slavery, they did not eliminate all forms of discrimination.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Along with literacy tests and durational residency requirements, poll taxes were used to keep low-income (primarily African American) citizens from participating in elections.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Supreme Court has since struck down these discriminatory measures.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Twenty-fifth Amendment clarifies what happens upon the death, removal, or resignation of the president or vice president and how the presidency is temporarily filled if the president becomes disabled and cannot fulfill the responsibilities of the office.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It supersedes the ambiguous succession rule established in Article II, Section 1, Clause 6.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] A concrete plan of succession has been needed on multiple occasions since 1789.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] However, for nearly 20% of U.S. history, there has been no vice president in office who could assume the presidency.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Twenty-sixth Amendment prohibits the government from denying the right of United States citizens, eighteen years of age or older, to vote on account of age.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The drive to lower the voting age was driven in large part by the broader student activism movement protesting the Vietnam War.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It gained strength following the Supreme Court's decision in *Oregon v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Twenty-seventh Amendment (1992) prevents members of Congress from granting themselves pay raises during the current session.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Rather, any raises that are adopted must take effect during the next session of Congress.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Its proponents believed that Federal legislators would be more likely to be cautious about increasing congressional pay if they have no personal stake in the vote.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Article One, Section 6, Clause 1 has been affected by this amendment, which remained pending for over two centuries as it contained no time limit for ratification.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Collectively, members of the House and Senate propose around 150 amendments during each two-year term of Congress.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Most however, never get out of the Congressional committees in which they are proposed, and only a fraction of those approved in committee receive sufficient support to win Congressional approval and actually enter the constitutional ratification process.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Six amendments approved by Congress and proposed to the states for consideration have not been ratified by the required number of states to become part of the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Four of these are technically still pending, as Congress did not set a time limit for their ratification.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The other two are no longer pending, as both had a time limit attached and in both cases the time period set for their ratification expired.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Courts established by the Constitution can regulate government under the Constitution, the supreme law of the land.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] First, they have jurisdiction over actions by an officer of government and state law.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Second, federal courts may rule on whether coordinate branches of national government conform to the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Until the twentieth century, the Supreme Court of the United States may have been the only high tribunal in the world to use a court for constitutional interpretation of fundamental law, others generally depending on their national legislature.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The basic theory of American judicial review is summarized by constitutional legal scholars and historians as follows: the written Constitution is fundamental law within the states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It can change only by extraordinary legislative process of national proposal, then state ratification.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The powers of all departments are limited to enumerated grants found in the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Courts are expected (a) to enforce provisions of the Constitution as the supreme law of the land, and (b) to refuse to enforce anything in conflict with it.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Judicial review relies on the jurisdictional authority in Article III, and the Supremacy Clause.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] When John Marshall followed Oliver Ellsworth as chief justice of the Supreme Court in 1801, the federal judiciary had been established by the Judiciary Act, but there were few cases.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Review of state legislation and appeals from state supreme courts was understood.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] But the Court's jurisdiction over state legislation was limited.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Marshall Court's landmark *Barron v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Baltimore* held that the Bill of Rights restricted only the federal government, and not the states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Madison* case, the Supreme Court asserted its authority of judicial review over Acts of Congress.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Its findings were that Marbury and the others had a right to their commissions as judges in the District of Columbia.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Marshall, writing the opinion for the majority, announced his discovered conflict between Section 13 of the Judiciary Act of 1789 and Article III.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] In this case, both the Constitution and the statutory law applied to the particulars at the same time.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] "The very essence of judicial duty" according to Marshall was to determine which of the two conflicting rules should govern.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Constitution enumerates powers of the judiciary to extend to cases arising "under the Constitution".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Supreme Court did not declare another act of Congress unconstitutional until the controversial Dred Scott decision in 1857, held after the voided Missouri Compromise statute had already been repealed.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] In the eighty years following the Civil War to World War II, the Court voided congressional statutes in 77 cases, on average almost one a year.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Chase was a Lincoln appointee, serving as chief justice from 1864 to 1873.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] In one of his first official acts, Chase admitted John Rock, the first African American to practice before the Supreme Court.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] White*, which asserted a permanent Union of indestructible states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Fenno* upheld the Civil War tax on state banknotes.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Griswold* found parts of the Legal Tender Acts unconstitutional, though it was reversed under a late Supreme Court majority.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] 3 (1883), were a group of five landmark cases in which the Supreme Court of the United States held that the Thirteenth and Fourteenth Amendments did not empower Congress to outlaw racial discrimination by private individuals.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The holding that the Thirteenth Amendment did not empower the federal government to punish racist acts done by private citizens would be overturned by the Supreme Court in the 1968 case *Jones v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Mayer Co.*The Fourteenth Amendment not applying to private entities, however, is still valid precedent to this day.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Although the Fourteenth Amendment-related decision has never been overturned, in the 1964 case of *Heart of Atlanta Motel, Inc. v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] United States*, the Supreme Court held that Congress could prohibit racial discrimination by private actors under the Commerce Clause.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] As chief justice, William Taft advocated for the Judiciary Act of 1925 that brought the Federal District Courts under the administrative jurisdiction of the Supreme Court.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1925, the Taft Court issued a ruling overturning a Marshall Court ruling on the Bill of Rights.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] New York*, the Court established the doctrine of "incorporation", which applied the Bill of Rights to the states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Important cases included the *Board of Trade of City of Chicago v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Olsen*, which upheld Congressional regulation of commerce; *Olmstead v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] United States*, which allowed exclusion of evidence obtained without a warrant based on application of the 14th Amendment proscription against unreasonable searches; and *Wisconsin v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Illinois*, which ruled the equitable power of the United States can impose positive action on a state to prevent its inaction from damaging another state.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] A crisis arose when, in 1935 and 1936, the Supreme Court handed down twelve decisions voiding acts of Congress relating to the New Deal.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt then responded with his abortive "court packing plan".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Other proposals have suggested a Court super-majority to overturn Congressional legislation, or a constitutional amendment to require that the justices retire at a specified age by law.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] To date, the Supreme Court's power of judicial review has persisted.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Earl Warren was an Eisenhower nominee, chief justice from 1953 to 1969.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1954, the Warren Court overturned a landmark Fuller Court ruling on the Fourteenth Amendment interpreting racial segregation as permissible in government and commerce providing "separate but equal" services.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Warren built a coalition of justices after 1962 that developed the idea of natural rights as guaranteed in the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Board of Education* banned segregation in public schools.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Sims* established Court ordered "one-man-one-vote".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Bill of Rights Amendments were incorporated into the states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Arizona.* First Amendment rights were addressed in *Griswold v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Connecticut* concerning privacy, and *Engel v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Warren E Burger was appointed by Richard Nixon.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Under his tenure, the Court decided the landmark cases of *Roe v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] William Rehnquist was a Reagan-appointed chief justice, serving from 1986 to 2005.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] While he would concur with overthrowing a state supreme court's decision, as in *Bush v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Gore*, he built a coalition of Justices after 1994 that developed the idea of federalism as provided for in the Tenth Amendment.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] In the hands of the Supreme Court, the Constitution and its amendments were to restrain Congress, as in *City of Boerne v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Nevertheless, the Rehnquist Court was noted in the contemporary "culture wars" for overturning state laws relating to privacy, prohibiting late-term abortions in *Stenberg v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Carhart*, prohibiting sodomy in *Lawrence v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Texas*, or ruling so as to protect free speech in *Texas v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Johnson* or affirmative action in *Grutter v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] John Roberts was appointed Chief Justice in 2005.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Supreme Court has developed a system of doctrine and practice that limits its own power of judicial review.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Court controls almost all of its business by choosing what cases to consider, limiting decisions by defining what is a "justiciable question".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Court requires a personal interest, not one generally held, and a legally protected right must be immediately threatened by government action.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Cases are not taken up if the litigant has no standing to sue.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Court also generally refuses to make any advisory opinions in advance of actual cases.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Further, friendly suits between those of the same legal interest are not considered.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The procedural ways by which the Court dismisses cases have led critics to charge that the Supreme Court delays decisions by unduly insisting on technicalities in their "standards of litigability".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] They say cases are left unconsidered which are in the public interest, with genuine controversy, and resulting from good faith action.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Supreme Court balances several pressures to maintain its roles in national government.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It seeks to be a co-equal branch of government, but its decrees must be enforceable.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Court seeks to minimize situations where it asserts itself superior to either president or Congress, but federal officers must be held accountable.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Supreme Court assumes power to declare acts of Congress as unconstitutional but it self-limits its passing on constitutional questions.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] But the Court's guidance on basic problems of life and governance in a democracy is most effective when American political life reinforces its rulings.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Justice Brandeis summarized four general guidelines that the Supreme Court uses to avoid constitutional decisions relating to Congress: The Court will not anticipate a question of constitutional law nor decide open questions unless a case decision requires it.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] If it does, a rule of constitutional law is formulated only as the precise facts in the case require.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Court will choose statutes or general law for the basis of its decision if it can without constitutional grounds.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] If it does, the Court will choose a constitutional construction of an act of Congress, even if its constitutionality is seriously in doubt.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Likewise with the executive department, Edwin Corwin observed that the Court does sometimes rebuff presidential pretensions, but it more often tries to rationalize them.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Against Congress, an act is merely "disallowed".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] In the executive case, exercising judicial review produces "some change in the external world" beyond the ordinary judicial sphere.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The "political question" doctrine especially applies to questions which present a difficult enforcement issue.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Chief Justice Charles Evans Hughes addressed the Court's limitation when political process allowed future policy change, but a judicial ruling would "attribute finality".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] John Marshall recognized that the president holds "important political powers" which as executive privilege allows great discretion.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] This doctrine was applied in Court rulings on President Grant's duty to enforce the law during Reconstruction.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It extends to the sphere of foreign affairs.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Justice Robert Jackson explained, foreign affairs are inherently political, "wholly confided by our Constitution to the political departments of the government ... [and] not subject to judicial intrusion or inquiry".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Critics of the Court object in two principal ways to self-restraint in judicial review, deferring as it does as a matter of doctrine to acts of Congress and presidential actions.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Its inaction is said to allow "a flood of legislative appropriations" which permanently create an imbalance between the states and federal government.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It has also been argued that the Supreme Court's deference to Congress and the executive compromises American protection of civil rights, political minority groups and aliens.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] There is a viewpoint that some Americans have come to see the documents of the Constitution, along with the Declaration of Independence and the Bill of Rights, as being a cornerstone of a type of civil religion.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Some commentators depict the multi-ethnic, multi-sectarian United States as held together by political orthodoxy, in contrast with a nation-state of people having more "natural" ties.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The United States Constitution has been a notable model for governance worldwide, especially through the 1970s.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Its international influence is found in similarities in phrasing and borrowed passages in other constitutions, as well as in the principles of the rule of law, separation of powers, and recognition of individual rights.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The American experience of fundamental law with amendments and judicial review has motivated constitutionalists at times when they were considering the possibilities for their nation's future.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It informed Abraham Lincoln during the American Civil War, his contemporary and ally Benito Juárez of Mexico, and the second generation of 19th-century constitutional nationalists, José Rizal of the Philippines and Sun Yat-sen of China.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The framers of the Australian constitution integrated federal ideas from the U.S. and other constitutions.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Since the 1980s, the influence of the United States Constitution has been waning as other countries have created new constitutions or updated older constitutions, a process which Sanford Levinson believes to be more difficult in the United States than in any other country.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The United States Constitution has faced various criticisms since its inception in 1787.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The Constitution did not originally define who was eligible to vote, allowing each state to determine who was eligible.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] In the early history of the U.S., most states allowed only white male adult property owners to vote; the notable exception was New Jersey, where women were able to vote on the same basis as men.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Until the Reconstruction Amendments were adopted between 1865 and 1870, the five years immediately following the American Civil War, the Constitution did not abolish slavery, nor give citizenship and voting rights to former slaves.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] These amendments did not include a specific prohibition on discrimination in voting on the basis of sex; it took another amendment—the Nineteenth, ratified in 1920—for the Constitution to prohibit any United States citizen from being denied the right to vote on the basis of sex.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] According to a 2012 study by David Law and Mila Versteeg published in the *New York University Law Review*, the U.S.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Constitution guarantees relatively few rights compared to the constitutions of other countries and contains fewer than half (26 of 60) of the provisions listed in the average bill of rights.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] It is also one of the few in the world today that still features the right to keep and bear arms; the other two being the constitutions of Guatemala and Mexico.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Sanford Levinson wrote in 2006 that it has been the most difficult constitution in the world to amend since the fall of Yugoslavia.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Post Office, at the prompting of President Franklin Delano Roosevelt, an avid stamp collector himself, released a commemorative postage stamp celebrating the 150th anniversary of the signing of the U.S.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The engraving on this issue is after an 1856 painting by Junius Brutus Stearns of Washington and shows delegates signing the Constitution at the 1787 Convention.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] The following year another commemorative stamp was issued celebrating the 150th anniversary of the ratification of the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/constitution-of-the-united-states-p02] Mint issued commemorative coins in celebration of the 200th anniversary of the signing of the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The **Democratic-Republican Party**, known at the time as the **Republican Party** (also referred to by historians as the **Jeffersonian Republican Party**), was an American political party founded by Thomas Jefferson and James Madison in the early 1790s.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] It championed liberalism, republicanism, individual liberty, equal rights, separation of church and state, freedom of religion, anti-clericalism, emancipation of religious minorities, decentralization, free markets, free trade, and agrarianism.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In foreign policy, it was hostile to Great Britain and sympathetic to the French Revolution and Napoleonic Wars.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The party became increasingly dominant after the 1800 elections as the opposing Federalist Party collapsed.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Increasing dominance over American politics also led to increasing factional splits within the party.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Republicans splintered during the 1824 presidential election.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Those calling for a return to the older founding principles of the party were often referred to as "Democratic Republicans" (later Democrats) while those embracing the newer nationalist principles of "The American System" were often referred to as National Republicans (later Whigs).
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Republican Party originated in Congress to oppose the nationalist and economically interventionist policies of Alexander Hamilton, who served as Secretary of the Treasury under President George Washington.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Republicans and the opposing Federalist Party each became more cohesive during Washington's second term, partly as a result of the debate over the Jay Treaty.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Though he was defeated by Federalist John Adams in the 1796 presidential election, Jefferson and his Republican allies came into power following the 1800 elections.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] As president, Jefferson presided over a reduction in the national debt and government spending, and completed the Louisiana Purchase with France.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Madison succeeded Jefferson as president in 1809 and led the country during the largely inconclusive War of 1812 with Britain.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] After the war, Madison and his congressional allies established the Second Bank of the United States and implemented protective tariffs, marking a move away from the party's earlier emphasis on states' rights and a strict construction of the United States Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Federalists collapsed after 1815, beginning a period known as the Era of Good Feelings.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Republicans were deeply committed to the principles of republicanism, which they feared were threatened by the aristocratic tendencies of the Federalists.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] During the 1790s, the party strongly opposed Federalist programs, including the national bank.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] After the War of 1812, Madison and many other party leaders came to accept the need for a national bank and federally funded infrastructure projects.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In foreign affairs, the party advocated western expansion and tended to favor France over Britain, though the party's pro-French stance faded after Napoleon took power.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Democratic-Republicans were strongest in the South and the western frontier, and weakest in New England.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In the 1788–89 presidential election, the first such election following the ratification of the United States Constitution in 1788, George Washington won the votes of every member of the Electoral College.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Washington selected Thomas Jefferson as Secretary of State and Alexander Hamilton as Secretary of the Treasury, and he relied on James Madison as a key adviser and ally in Congress.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Hamilton implemented an expansive economic program, establishing the First Bank of the United States, and convincing Congress to assume the debts of state governments.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Hamilton pursued his programs in the belief that they would foster a prosperous and stable country.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] His policies engendered an opposition, chiefly concentrated in the Southern United States, that objected to Hamilton's Anglophilia and accused him of unduly favoring well-connected wealthy Northern merchants and speculators.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Madison emerged as the leader of the congressional opposition while Jefferson, who declined to publicly criticize Hamilton while both served in Washington's Cabinet, worked behind the scenes to stymie Hamilton's programs.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Jefferson and Madison, leading an Anti-Administration group, established the *National Gazette*, a newspaper which recast national politics not as a battle between Federalists and Anti-Federalists, but as a debate between aristocrats and republicans.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In the 1792 election, Washington effectively ran unopposed for president, but Jefferson and Madison backed New York Governor George Clinton's unsuccessful attempt to unseat Vice President John Adams.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Political leaders on both sides were reluctant to label their respective faction as a political party, but distinct and consistent voting blocs emerged in Congress by the end of 1793.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Jefferson's followers became known as the Republicans (or sometimes as the Democratic-Republicans) and Hamilton's followers (the Pro-Administration group) became the Federalists.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] While economic policies were the original motivating factor in the growing partisan split, foreign policy became even more important as war broke out between Great Britain (favored by Federalists) and France, which Republicans favored until 1799.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Partisan tensions escalated as a result of the Whiskey Rebellion and Washington's subsequent denunciation of the Democratic-Republican Societies, a type of new local political societies that favored democracy and generally supported the Jeffersonian position.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Historians use the term "Democratic-Republican" to describe these new organizations, but that name was rarely used at the time.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] They usually called themselves "Democratic", "Republican", "True Republican", "Constitutional", "United Freeman", "Patriotic", "Political", "Franklin", or "Madisonian".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The ratification of the Jay Treaty with Britain further inflamed partisan warfare, resulting in a hardening of the divisions between the Federalists and the Republicans.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] By 1795–96, election campaigns—federal, state and local—were waged primarily along partisan lines between the two national parties, although local issues continued to affect elections, and party affiliations remained in flux.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] As Washington declined to seek a third term, the 1796 presidential election became the first contested president election.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Having retired from Washington's Cabinet in 1793, Jefferson had left the leadership of the Democratic-Republicans in Madison's hands.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Nonetheless, the Democratic-Republican congressional nominating caucus chose Jefferson as the party's presidential nominee, in the belief that he would be the party's strongest candidate; the caucus chose Senator Aaron Burr of New York as Jefferson's running mate.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Meanwhile, an informal caucus of Federalist leaders nominated a ticket of John Adams and Thomas Pinckney.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Though the candidates themselves largely stayed out of the fray, supporters of the candidates waged an active campaign; Federalists attacked Jefferson as a Francophile and atheist, while the Democratic-Republicans accused Adams of being an anglophile and a monarchist.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Ultimately, Adams won the presidency by a narrow margin, garnering 71 electoral votes to 68 for Jefferson, who became the vice president.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Shortly after Adams took office, he dispatched a group of envoys to seek peaceful relations with France, which had begun seizing American merchantmen trading with Britain after the ratification of the Jay Treaty.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The failure of talks, and the French demand for bribes in what became known as the XYZ Affair, outraged the American public and led to the Quasi-War, an undeclared naval war between France and the United States.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Federalist-controlled Congress passed measures to expand the American military and also pushed through the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] These acts restricted speech critical of the government while also implementing stricter naturalization requirements.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Numerous journalists and other individuals aligned with the Democratic-Republicans were prosecuted under the Sedition Act, sparking a backlash against the Federalists.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Meanwhile, Jefferson and Madison drafted the Kentucky and Virginia Resolutions, which held that state legislatures could determine the constitutionality of federal laws.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In the 1800 presidential election, the Democratic-Republicans once again nominated a ticket of Jefferson and Burr.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Shortly after a Federalist caucus re-nominated President Adams on a ticket with Charles Cotesworth Pinckney, Adams dismissed two Hamilton allies from his Cabinet, leading to an open break between the two key figures in the Federalist Party.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Though the Federalist Party united against Jefferson's candidacy and waged an effective campaign in many states, the Democratic-Republicans won the election by winning most Southern electoral votes and carrying the crucial state of New York.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] A significant element in the party's success in New York City, Philadelphia, Baltimore and other east-coast cities were United Irish exiles, and other Irish immigrants, whom the Federalists regarded with distinct suspicion.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Among these was William Duane who in his newspaper, the *Philadelphia Aurora*, exposed the details of the Ross Bill, by means of which the Federalist-controlled Congress sought to establish a closed-door Grand Committee with powers to disqualify College electors.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Adams was to name Duane one of the three or four men most responsible for his eventual defeat.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Jefferson and Burr both finished with 73 electoral votes, more than Adams or Pinckney, necessitating a contingent election between Jefferson and Burr in the House of Representatives.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Burr declined to take his name out of consideration, and the House deadlocked as most Democratic-Republican congressmen voted for Jefferson and most Federalists voted for Burr.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Preferring Jefferson to Burr, Hamilton helped engineer Jefferson's election on the 36th ballot of the contingent election.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Ideology played a central role with a Jeffersonian "left" supporting the French Revolution, versus a Federalist "right" opposing it.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Despite the intensity of the 1800 election, the transition of power from the Federalists to the Democratic-Republicans was peaceful.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In his inaugural address, Jefferson indicated that he would seek to reverse many Federalist policies, but he also emphasized reconciliation, noting that "every difference of opinion is not a difference of principle".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Gallatin persuaded Jefferson to retain the First Bank of the United States, a major part of the Hamiltonian program, but other Federalist policies were scrapped.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Jefferson and his Democratic-Republican allies eliminated the whiskey excise and other taxes, shrank the army and the navy, repealed the Alien and Sedition Acts, and pardoned all ten individuals who had been prosecuted under the acts.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] With the repeal of Federalist laws and programs, many Americans had little contact with the federal government in their daily lives, with the exception of the postal service.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Partly as a result of these spending cuts, Jefferson lowered the national debt from $83 million to $57 million between 1801 and 1809.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Though he was largely able to reverse Federalist policies, Federalists retained a bastion of power on the Supreme Court; Marshall Court rulings continued to reflect Federalist ideals until Chief Justice Marshall's death in the 1830s.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In the Supreme Court case of *Marbury v.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Madison*, the Marshall Court established the power of judicial review, through which the judicial branch had the final word on the constitutionality of federal laws.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] By the time Jefferson took office, Americans had settled as far west as the Mississippi River.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Many in the United States, particularly those in the west, favored further territorial expansion, and especially hoped to annex the Spanish province of Louisiana.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In early 1803, Jefferson dispatched James Monroe to France to join ambassador Robert Livingston on a diplomatic mission to purchase New Orleans.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] To the surprise of the American delegation, Napoleon offered to sell the entire territory of Louisiana for $15 million.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] After Secretary of State James Madison gave his assurances that the purchase was well within even the strictest interpretation of the Constitution, the Senate quickly ratified the treaty, and the House immediately authorized funding.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Louisiana Purchase nearly doubled the size of the United States, and Treasury Secretary Gallatin was forced to borrow from foreign banks to finance the payment to France.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] By 1804, Vice President Burr had thoroughly alienated Jefferson, and the Democratic-Republican presidential nominating caucus chose George Clinton as Jefferson's running mate for the 1804 presidential election.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] That same year, Burr challenged Hamilton to a duel after taking offense to a comment allegedly made by Hamilton; Hamilton died in the subsequent duel.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Bolstered by a superior party organization, Jefferson won the 1804 election in a landslide over Federalist candidate Charles Cotesworth Pinckney.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In 1807, as the Napoleonic Wars continued, the British government announced the Orders in Council, which called for a blockade on French-controlled ports.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In response to subsequent British and French searches of American shipping, the Jefferson administration passed the Embargo Act of 1807, which cut off American trade with Europe.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The embargo proved unpopular and difficult to enforce, especially in Federalist-leaning New England, and expired at the end of Jefferson's second term.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Jefferson declined to seek a third term in the 1808 presidential election, but helped Madison triumph over George Clinton and James Monroe at the party's congressional nominating caucus.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Madison won the general election in a landslide over Pinckney.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] As attacks on American shipping continued after Madison took office, both Madison and the broader American public moved towards war.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Public resentment towards Britain led to the election of a new generation of Democratic-Republican leaders, including Henry Clay and John C.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Calhoun, who championed high tariffs, federally funded internal improvements and a jingoistic attitude towards Britain.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] On June 1, 1812, Madison asked Congress for a declaration of war.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The declaration was passed largely along sectional and party lines, with intense opposition coming from the Federalists and some other congressmen from the Northeast.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] For many who favored war, national honor was at stake; John Quincy Adams wrote that the only alternative to war was "the abandonment of our right as an independent nation." George Clinton's nephew, DeWitt Clinton, challenged Madison in the 1812 presidential election.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Though Clinton assembled a formidable coalition of Federalists and anti-Madison Democratic-Republicans, Madison won a close election.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Madison initially hoped for a quick end to the War of 1812, but the war got off to a disastrous start as multiple American invasions of Canada were defeated.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The United States had more military success in 1813, and American troops under William Henry Harrison defeated Tecumseh's confederacy in the Battle of the Thames in 1814, crushing Indian resistance to U.S. expansion.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Britain shifted troops to North America in 1814 following Napoleon's abdication, and British forces captured and burnt Washington in August 1814.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In early 1815, Madison learned that his negotiators in Europe had signed the Treaty of Ghent, ending the war without major concessions by either side.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Though it had no effect on the treaty, Andrew Jackson's victory in the January 1815 Battle of New Orleans ended the war on a triumphant note.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Napoleon's defeat at the Battle of Waterloo in June 1815 brought a final end to the Napoleonic Wars and European interference with American shipping.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] With Americans celebrating a successful "second war of independence", the Federalist Party slid towards national irrelevance.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In his first term, Madison and his allies had largely hewed to Jefferson's domestic agenda of low taxes and a reduction of the national debt, and Congress allowed the national bank's charter to expire during Madison's first term.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The challenges of the War of 1812 led many Democratic-Republicans to reconsider the role of the federal government.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] When the 14th Congress convened in December 1815, Madison proposed the re-establishment of the national bank, increased spending on the army and the navy, and a tariff designed to protect American goods from foreign competition.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] At the party's 1816 congressional nominating caucus, Secretary of State James Monroe defeated Secretary of War William H.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Federalists offered little opposition in the 1816 presidential election and Monroe won in a landslide election.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Monroe believed that the existence of political parties was harmful to the United States, and he sought to usher in the end of the Federalist Party by avoiding divisive policies and welcoming ex-Federalists into the fold.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Monroe favored infrastructure projects to promote economic development and, despite some constitutional concerns, signed bills providing federal funding for the National Road and other projects.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Partly due to the mismanagement of national bank president William Jones, the country experienced a prolonged economic recession known as the Panic of 1819.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The panic engendered a widespread resentment of the national bank and a distrust of paper money that would influence national politics long after the recession ended.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Despite the ongoing economic troubles, the Federalists failed to field a serious challenger to Monroe in the 1820 presidential election, and Monroe won re-election essentially unopposed.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] During the proceedings over the admission of Missouri Territory as a state, Congressman James Tallmadge, Jr. of New York "tossed a bombshell into the Era of Good Feelings" by proposing amendments providing for the eventual exclusion of slavery from Missouri.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The amendments sparked the first major national slavery debate since the ratification of the Constitution, and instantly exposed the sectional polarization over the issue of slavery.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Northern Democratic-Republicans formed a coalition across partisan lines with the remnants of the Federalist Party in support of the amendments, while Southern Democratic-Republicans were almost unanimously against such the restrictions.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Thomas of Illinois proposed a compromise, in which Missouri would be admitted as a slave state, but slavery would be excluded in the remaining territories north of the parallel 36°30′ north.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] A bill based on Thomas's proposal became law in April 1820.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] By 1824, the Federalist Party had largely collapsed as a national party, and the 1824 presidential election was waged by competing members of the Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The party's congressional nominating caucus was largely ignored, and candidates were instead nominated by state legislatures.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Secretary of State John Quincy Adams, former Speaker of the House Henry Clay, Secretary of the Treasury William Crawford, and General Andrew Jackson emerged as the major candidates in the election.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The regional strength of each candidate played an important role in the election; Adams was popular in New England, Clay and Jackson were strong in the West, and Jackson and Crawford competed for the South.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] As no candidate won a majority of the electoral vote in the 1824 election, the House of Representatives held a contingent election to determine the president.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Clay personally disliked Adams but nonetheless supported him in the contingent election over Crawford, who opposed Clay's nationalist policies, and Jackson, whom Clay viewed as a potential tyrant.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] With Clay's backing, Adams won the contingent election.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] After Clay accepted appointment as Secretary of State, Jackson's supporters claimed that Adams and Clay had reached a "Corrupt Bargain" in which Adams promised Clay the appointment in return for Clay's support in the contingent election.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Jackson, who was deeply angered by the result of the contingent election, returned to Tennessee, where the state legislature quickly nominated him for president in the 1828 election.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Adams shared Monroe's goal of ending partisan conflict, and his Cabinet included individuals of various ideological and regional backgrounds.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In his 1825 annual message to Congress, Adams presented a comprehensive and ambitious agenda, calling for major investments in internal improvements as well as the creation of a national university, a naval academy, and a national astronomical observatory.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] His requests to Congress galvanized the opposition, spurring the creation of an anti-Adams congressional coalition consisting of supporters of Jackson, Crawford, and Vice President Calhoun.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Following the 1826 elections, Calhoun and Martin Van Buren (who brought along many of Crawford's supporters) agreed to throw their support behind Jackson in the 1828 election.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In the press, the two major political factions were referred to as "Adams Men" and "Jackson Men".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Jacksonians formed an effective party apparatus that adopted many modern campaign techniques and emphasized Jackson's popularity and the supposed corruption of Adams and the federal government.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Though Jackson did not articulate a detailed political platform in the same way that Adams did, his coalition was united in opposition to Adams's reliance on government planning and tended to favor the opening of Native American lands to white settlement.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Ultimately, Jackson won 178 of the 261 electoral votes and just under 56 percent of the popular vote.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Jackson won 50.3 percent of the popular vote in the free states and 72.6 percent of the vote in the slave states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The election marked the permanent end of the Era of Good Feelings and the start of the Second Party System.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The dream of non-partisan politics, shared by Monroe, Adams, and many earlier leaders, was shattered, replaced with Van Buren's ideal of partisan battles between legitimated political parties.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In the 1790s, political parties were new in the United States and people were not accustomed to having formal names for them.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] There was no single official name for the Democratic-Republican Party, but party members generally called themselves Republicans and voted for what they called the "Republican party", "republican ticket" or "republican interest".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Jefferson and Madison often used the terms "republican" and "Republican party" in their letters.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The term "Democratic-Republican" was used by contemporaries only occasionally, but is used by modern political scientists.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Historians often refer to the "Jeffersonian Republicans".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The term "Democratic Party" was first used pejoratively by Federalist opponents.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Democratic-Republican Party saw itself as a champion of republicanism and denounced the Federalists as supporters of monarchy and aristocracy.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Ralph Brown writes that the party was marked by a "commitment to broad principles of personal liberty, social mobility, and westward expansion." Political scientist James A.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Influenced by the Jeffersonian belief in equality, by 1824 all but three states had removed property-owning requirements for voting.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Though open to some redistributive measures, Jefferson saw a strong centralized government as a threat to freedom.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Thus, the Democratic-Republicans opposed Federalist efforts to build a strong, centralized state, and resisted the establishment of a national bank, the build-up of the army and the navy, and passage of the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Jefferson was especially averse to a national debt, which he believed to be inherently dangerous and immoral.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] After the party took power in 1800, Jefferson became increasingly concerned about foreign intervention and more open to programs of economic development conducted by the federal government.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In an effort to promote economic growth and the development of a diversified economy, Jefferson's Democratic-Republican successors would oversee the construction of numerous federally funded infrastructure projects and implement protective tariffs.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] While economic policies were the original catalyst to the partisan split between the Democratic-Republicans and the Federalists, foreign policy was also a major factor that divided the parties.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Most Americans supported the French Revolution prior to the Execution of Louis XVI in 1793, but Federalists began to fear the radical egalitarianism of the revolution as it became increasingly violent.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Jefferson and other Democratic-Republicans defended the French Revolution until Napoleon ascended to power.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Democratic-Republican foreign policy was marked by support for expansionism, as Jefferson championed the concept of an "Empire of Liberty" that centered on the acquisition and settlement of western territories.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Under Jefferson, Madison, and Monroe, the United States completed the Louisiana Purchase, acquired Spanish Florida, and reached a treaty with Britain providing for shared sovereignty over Oregon Country.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In 1823, the Monroe administration promulgated the Monroe Doctrine, which reiterated the traditional U.S. policy of neutrality with regard to European wars and conflicts, but declared that the United States would not accept the recolonization of any country by its former European master.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] From the foundation of the party, slavery divided the Democratic-Republicans.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Many Southern Democratic-Republicans, especially from the Deep South, defended the institution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Jefferson and many other Democratic-Republicans from Virginia held an ambivalent view on slavery; Jefferson believed it was an immoral institution, but he opposed the immediate emancipation of all slaves on social and economic grounds.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Instead, he favored gradual phasing out of the institution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Meanwhile, Northern Democratic-Republicans often took stronger anti-slavery positions than their Federalist counterparts, supporting measures like the abolition of slavery in Washington.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In 1807, with President Jefferson's support, Congress outlawed the international slave trade, doing so at the earliest possible date allowed by the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] After the War of 1812, Southerners increasingly came to view slavery as a beneficial institution rather than an unfortunate economic necessity, further polarizing the party over the issue.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Anti-slavery Northern Democratic-Republicans held that slavery was incompatible with the equality and individual rights promised by the Declaration of Independence and the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] They further held that slavery had been permitted under the Constitution only as a local and impermanent exception, and thus, slavery should not be allowed to spread outside of the original thirteen states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The anti-slavery positions developed by Northern Democratic-Republicans would influence later anti-slavery parties, including the Free Soil Party and the Republican Party.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Madison and Jefferson formed the Democratic-Republican Party from a combination of former Anti-Federalists and supporters of the Constitution who were dissatisfied with the Washington administration's policies.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Nationwide, Democratic-Republicans were strongest in the South, and many of party's leaders were wealthy Southern slaveowners.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Democratic-Republicans also attracted middle class Northerners, such as artisans, farmers, and lower-level merchants, who were eager to challenge the power of the local elite.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Every state had a distinct political geography that shaped party membership; in Pennsylvania, the Republicans were weakest around Philadelphia and strongest in Scots-Irish settlements in the west.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Federalists had broad support in New England, but in other places they relied on wealthy merchants and landowners.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] After 1800, the Federalists collapsed in the South and West, though the party remained competitive in New England and in some Mid-Atlantic states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Historian Sean Wilentz writes that, after assuming power in 1801, the Democratic-Republicans began to factionalize into three main groups: moderates, radicals, and Old Republicans.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Old Republicans, led by John Randolph, were a loose group of influential Southern plantation owners who strongly favored states' rights and denounced any form of compromise with the Federalists.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The moderate faction consisted of many former supporters of the ratification of the Constitution, including James Madison, who were more accepting of Federalist economic programs and sought conciliation with moderate Federalists.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] After 1810, a younger group of nationalist Democratic-Republicans, led by Henry Clay and John C.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] These nationalists favored federally funded internal improvements and high tariffs, positions that would form the basis for Clay's American System.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In addition to its base among the leaders of Clay and Calhoun's generation, nationalist policies also proved attractive to many older Democratic-Republicans, including James Monroe.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Panic of 1819 sparked a backlash against nationalist policies, and many of those opposed to the nationalist policies rallied around William H.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Crawford until he had a major stroke in 1823.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] After the 1824 election, most of Crawford's followers, including Martin Van Buren, gravitated to Andrew Jackson, forming a major part of the coalition that propelled Jackson to victory in the 1828 election.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Democratic-Republican Party invented campaign and organizational techniques that were later adopted by the Federalists and became standard American practice.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] It was especially effective in building a network of newspapers in major cities to broadcast its statements and editorialize its policies.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Fisher Ames, a leading Federalist, used the term "Jacobin" to link members of Jefferson's party to the radicals of the French Revolution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] He blamed the newspapers for electing Jefferson and wrote they were "an overmatch for any Government....
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Jacobins owe their triumph to the unceasing use of this engine; not so much to skill in use of it as by repetition".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] As one historian explained: "It was the good fortune of the Republicans to have within their ranks a number of highly gifted political manipulators and propagandists.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Some of them had the ability... to not only see and analyze the problem at hand but to present it in a succinct fashion; in short, to fabricate the apt phrase, to coin the compelling slogan and appeal to the electorate on any given issue in language it could understand".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Outstanding propagandists included editor William Duane (1760–1835) and party leaders Albert Gallatin, Thomas Cooper and Jefferson himself.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Just as important was effective party organization of the sort that John J.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In 1796, he managed the Jefferson campaign in Pennsylvania, blanketing the state with agents who passed out 30,000 hand-written tickets, naming all 15 electors (printed tickets were not allowed).
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Beckley told one agent: "In a few days a select republican friend from the City will call upon you with a parcel of tickets to be distributed in your County.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Any assistance and advice you can furnish him with, as to suitable districts & characters, will I am sure be rendered".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Beckley was the first American professional campaign manager and his techniques were quickly adopted in other states.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The emergence of the new organizational strategies can be seen in the politics of Connecticut around 1806, which have been well documented by Cunningham.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Federalists dominated Connecticut, so the Republicans had to work harder to win.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In 1806, the state leadership sent town leaders instructions for the forthcoming elections.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Every town manager was told by state leaders "to appoint a district manager in each district or section of his town, obtaining from each an assurance that he will faithfully do his duty".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] These highly detailed returns were to be sent to the county manager and in turn were compiled and sent to the state manager.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Using these lists of potential voters, the managers were told to get all eligible people to town meetings and help the young men qualify to vote.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The state manager was responsible for supplying party newspapers to each town for distribution by town and district managers.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] This highly coordinated "get-out-the-vote" drive would be familiar to future political campaigners, but was the first of its kind in world history.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] After the 1824 presidential election the Democratic-Republicans split into factions.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The coalition of Jacksonians, Calhounites, and Crawfordites built by Andrew Jackson and Martin Van Buren coalesced into the Democratic Party, which dominated presidential politics in the decades prior to the Civil War.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Supporters of John Quincy Adams and Henry Clay would form the main opposition to Jackson as the National Republican Party, which in turn eventually formed part of the Whig Party, which was the second major party in the United States between the 1830s and the early 1850s.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The diverse and changing nature of the Democratic-Republican Party allowed both major parties to claim that they stood for Jeffersonian principles.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Whig Party fell apart in the 1850s due to divisions over the expansion of slavery into new territories.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The modern Republican Party was formed in 1854 to oppose the expansion of slavery, and many former Whig Party leaders joined the newly formed anti-slavery party.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Republican Party sought to combine Jefferson and Jackson's ideals of liberty and equality with Clay's program of using an active government to modernize the economy.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The Democratic-Republican Party inspired the name of its two direct descendants or offshoots: the National Republican Party (Whigs) and the Democratic party, as well as the later newly created Republican Party.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Fear of a large debt is a major legacy of this party.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Andrew Jackson believed the national debt was a "national curse" and he took special pride in paying off the entire national debt in 1835.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Politicians ever since have used the issue of a high national debt to denounce the other party for profligacy and a threat to fiscal soundness and the nation's future.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] In their second presidential run, Jefferson and Burr received the same number of electoral votes.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Jefferson was subsequently chosen as President by the House of Representatives.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] While commonly labeled as the Federalist candidate, Clinton technically ran as a Democratic-Republican and was not nominated by the Federalist party itself, the latter simply deciding not to field a candidate.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] This did not prevent endorsements from state Federalist parties (such as in Pennsylvania), but he received the endorsement from the New York state Democratic-Republicans as well.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Crawford and Albert Gallatin were nominated for president and vice-president by a group of 66 Congressmen that called itself the "Democratic members of Congress".
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Gallatin later withdrew from the contest.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Andrew Jackson, John Quincy Adams and Henry Clay ran as Republicans, although they were not nominated by any national body.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] While Jackson won a plurality in the electoral college and popular vote, he did not win the constitutionally required majority of electoral votes to be elected president.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The contest was thrown to the House of Representatives, where Adams won with Clay's support.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The affiliation of many Congressmen in the earliest years is an assignment by later historians.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] The parties were slowly coalescing groups; at first there were many independents.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/democratic-republican-party-united-states] Cunningham noted that only about a quarter of the House of Representatives up until 1794 voted with Madison as much as two-thirds of the time and another quarter against him two-thirds of the time, leaving almost half as fairly independent.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/duncan-mcfarlan] Born in Laurel Hill, North Carolina in Scotland County, McFarlan engaged in agricultural pursuits.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/duncan-mcfarlan] He served in the North Carolina House of Commons in 1792 and the North Carolina Senate in 1793, 1795 and 1800.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/duncan-mcfarlan] At the 1788 Hillsborough Convention, he voted against the ratification of the US Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/duncan-mcfarlan] McFarlan stood for election to Congress in 1802, but was unsuccessful; he ran again in 1804 and served one term, in the 9th United States Congress (March 4, 1805 – March 3, 1807).
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/duncan-mcfarlan] After his term in Washington, McFarlan returned to North Carolina and engaged in mercantile and agricultural pursuits, serving one further term in the state Senate, from 1807 to 1809.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/duncan-mcfarlan] He died at Laurel Hill in 1816 and is buried in Laurel Hill Cemetery.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] The **Hillsborough Convention** was the first of two North Carolina conventions to ratify the United States Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] Delegates represented 7 boroughs and 59 counties, including six western counties that became part of Tennessee when it was created in 1796.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] They met in Hillsborough, North Carolina from July 21 to August 4, 1788 to deliberate and determine whether to ratify the Constitution recommended to the states by the General Convention that had been held in Philadelphia the previous summer.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] The delegates had won their seats through special elections held in March 1788, as mandated by the North Carolina General Assembly.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] Governor Samuel Johnston presided over the Convention.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] The Hillsborough Convention was dominated by anti-Federalists, and North Carolina did not ratify the Constitution until the Fayetteville Convention, which met a year later.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] The church building was located on Lot 98 in Hillsborough.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] It was also the location of the third Provincial Congress of North Carolina of 1775 and the meeting place of the North Carolina Legislature in 1778, 1782 and 1783.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] The church was destroyed by fire before 1800s.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] A new structure was built on the site in 1814 and became the Hillsborough Presbyterian Church in 1816.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] Key state Federalists were James Iredell Sr., William Richardson Davie, and William Blount.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] Anti-Federalist leaders included Willie Jones, Samuel Spencer, and Timothy Bloodworth.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] The Anti-Federalist delegates outnumbered their Federalist colleagues by a margin of two to one.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] The Federalists wanted to strengthen the powers of the federal government to help the country keep from dissolving.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] They argued that the powers granted to the federal government in the Articles of Confederation were not sufficient.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] On the other side, the Anti-Federalists were suspicious of the federal government and did not want self-rule to come under fire from a government that could intrude on state and individual rights.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] Knowing that they would likely lose, members of the Federalist minority brought a stenographer to the convention to record their arguments for publication in the hopes of changing public opinion in the future.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] The debate resulted in the delegates voting 184 to 84 to neither ratify nor reject the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] One of the major reasons for North Carolina not ratifying the Constitution was its lack of a Bill of Rights.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] The delegates, however, proposed a series of amendments to personal liberties and urged the new federal Congress to adopt measures to incorporate a bill of rights into the Constitution.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] North Carolina would not join the Union until after it ratified the Constitution, more than a year later, at the November 1789 Fayetteville Convention.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] There were 294 known delegates from the 59 counties and seven boroughs of North Carolina.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] Some counties (Greene, Sullivan, Sumner, Tennessee, Washington) later became part of the state of Tennessee in 1796.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] The election of delegates from Dobbs County was declared invalid because of violence that led to the loss of the ballot box.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] Governor Samuel Johnston was the President of the Convention.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] While his home was in Chowan County, he represented Perquimans County in the Convention.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] John Hunt was the secretary and James Taylor was the assistant secretary of the Convention.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/hillsborough-convention] The doorkeepers of the convention were William Murfree, Peter Gooding, Nicholas Murfree, and James Mulloy.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/john-culpepper] John Culpeper of Albemarle, leader of Culpeper's Rebellion in 1677, was Culpepper's third great uncle.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/john-culpepper] Culpepper attended the public schools; became a minister and pastored Rocky River Baptist Church for fifty years; Under the authority of the Third North Carolina General Assembly during the American Revolution, Montgomery County, North Carolina was formed in 1779 from a portion of Anson County.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/john-culpepper] Congressional Districts that contained both counties.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/john-culpepper] District boundaries have been redefined each decade in the year following each national census since the 1790 census.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/john-culpepper] He was deemed a man of sound sense, but not brilliant, useful rather than showy.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/john-culpepper] Culpepper died at the residence of his son in Darlington County, South Carolina in January 1841; interment in the cemetery at Society Hill, South Carolina.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/laurel-hill-scotland-county-north-carolina] In 1797 the Laurel Hill Presbyterian Church was established.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/laurel-hill-scotland-county-north-carolina] The church was named for the laurel growing in the area.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/laurel-hill-scotland-county-north-carolina] A community formed in the vicinity of the church, and after the American Revolutionary War it prospered as a center of commerce.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/laurel-hill-scotland-county-north-carolina] Most of the initial settlers were Scottish Highlanders.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/laurel-hill-scotland-county-north-carolina] A line of the Wilmington, Charlotte and Rutherford Railroad was later laid and a depot established to the south of the church area, and by 1861 most of the community had migrated there.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/laurel-hill-scotland-county-north-carolina] A turpentine distillery and tub manufacturer were established.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/laurel-hill-scotland-county-north-carolina] Federal troops under William Tecumseh Sherman camped by the church in 1865 during the Carolinas campaign of the American Civil War.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/laurel-hill-scotland-county-north-carolina] McNair created a general store in Laurel Hill.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/laurel-hill-scotland-county-north-carolina] Pate purchased McNair's general store and transformed it into a large regional furniture retailer.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/laurel-hill-scotland-county-north-carolina] Beginning in 2004, the community has hosted an annual festival, LaurelFest.
[src:duncan-mcfarlan/laurel-hill-scotland-county-north-carolina] In 2020 the local community center was demolished and the Scotland County Commission contracted construction of a new one the following year.
